Problem Statement:

The dataset on American College and University Rankings contains information on 1302 American colleges and universities offering an undergraduate program. For each university, there are 17 measurements, including continuous measurements (such as tuition and grad- uation rate) and categorical measurements (such as location by state and whether it is a private or public school). Note that many records are missing some measurements.

kMeans Clustering : It is an unsupervised learning algorithm. K-means algorithm identifies k number of centroids, and then allocates every data point to the nearest cluster, while keeping the centroids as small as possible.

  • The libraries required to proceed with the solution by implementing the k Means Clustering algorithm.

Q 2.) For all the continuous measurements, run K-Means clustering. Make sure to normalize the measurements. How many clusters seem reasonable for describing these data? What was your optimal K?

  • To normalized the dataset we have scale the continuous variables of the date by its z-score.
Normalized_University <- scale(University[c(-1,-2,-3)])

To compute the optimal k value we can use:

  • With-In-Sum-Of-Squares (WSS) method. WSS is a measure to explain the homogeneity within a cluster. WSS is the total distance of data points from their respective cluster centroids

  • Average Silhouette measures the quality of a clustering,it determines how well each object lies within its cluster. A high average silhouette width indicates a good clustering.

fviz_nbclust(Normalized_University, kmeans, method = "wss")

fviz_nbclust(Normalized_University, kmeans, method = "silhouette")

Here if we look carefully, the optimal solution for k value iscomputed as 3. Therefore, we can now use this k = 3 to apply the k means clustering algorithm on the dataset. However considering thecatagorical measurements the reasonable number of cluster to be formed should be 2 for Private College and Public Colleges.

Q 3.) Compare the summary statistics for each cluster and describe each cluster in this context (e.g., Universities with high tuition, low acceptance rate).

k_means <- kmeans(Normalized_University, centers = 3, nstart = 50)

View(k_means$centers)
k_means$size
## [1] 275 150  46
fviz_cluster(k_means, data = Normalized_University)

Based on the computed summary of the clusters we can predict the below conclusions:

  • Cluster 1 : Below Average College.

Applications received - Low Application Accepted - Low New Enrollement - Low Percentage of new students from top 10% - Low Percentage of new students from top 25% - Low Full Time undergrade - Low Part Time undergrade - Low In state tution - Average Out state tution - Average Room Cost - Average Boards - Average Additional fees - Low Estimated Book Cost - Low Estimated Personal Expenses - Average Faculty with PHD - Average Student/Facult Ratio - Average Graduation Rate - Low

Cluster 2 : Average College.

Applications received - High Application Accepted - High New Enrollement - High Percentage of new students from top 10% - Average Percentage of new students from top 25% - Average Full Time undergrade - High Part Time undergrade - High In state tution - Average Out state tution - Average Room Cost - Low Boards - Low Additional fees - High Estimated Book Cost - High Estimated Personal Expenses - High Faculty with PHD - Low Student/Facult Ratio - High Graduation Rate - Average

  • Cluster 3 : Best Average.

Applications received - Average Application Accepted - Average New Enrollement - Average Percentage of new students from top 10% - High Percentage of new students from top 25% - High Full Time undergrade - Average Part Time undergrade - Average In state tution - High Out state tution - High Room Cost - High Boards - High Additional fees - Average Estimated Book Cost - Average Estimated Personal Expenses - Low Faculty with PHD - High Student/Facult Ratio - Low Graduation Rate - High

Hence based on the above calculations we can predict that the Universities in the Cluster 3 can be Best Universities to study at, average universities will be in Cluster 2 and Below Average universities would be in Cluster 3.

k_means$totss
## [1] 7990
k_means$withinss
## [1] 2562.342 1424.892 1044.680
k_means$betweenss
## [1] 2958.086
k_means$iter
## [1] 3

  • Total-Sum-of-Squares (TSS): TSS is the total distance of data points from global mean of data, for a given dataset this quantity is going to be constant = 7990

  • With-in-Sum-of-Squares (WSS): WSS is the total distance of data points from their respective cluster centroid = Cluster 1 : 2562.342, Cluster 2 : 1424.892, Cluster 3 : 1044.680

  • Between-Sum-of-Squares (BSS): BSS is the total weighted distance of various cluster centroids to the global mean of data = 2958.086

  • Iter: The number of (outer) iterations = 3

Q 6.) Consider Tufts University, which is missing some information. Compute the Euclidean distance of this record from each of the clusters that you found above (using only the measurements that you have). Which cluster is it closest to? Impute the missing values for Tufts by taking the average of the cluster on those measurements.

  • Here, we have added a row of Tufts University which we have computed above and added the mean value of the data in place of the missing values in the dataset.
Data <- rbind(University, Tufts_university)
dim(Data)
## [1] 472  20
  • The data needs to be normalized based on the same method (scale i.e.z-score) as the kMeans Model we have computed above.
Data_normalized <- scale(Data[c(-1,-2,-3)])
  • We have computed the distance of all the dataset.
Distance_Tuft <- get_dist(Data_normalized)
fviz_dist(Distance_Tuft)

  • Applying the kMeans Clustering Model with optimal k = 3. Later, we have bind the Tufts University data with the cluster it falls under after the k means Clustering model is applied
k_means_Tufts <- kmeans(Data_normalized, centers = 3, nstart = 50)

cbind(Tufts_university, Cluster = tail(k_means_Tufts$cluster, 1))
